<Layout title="Treatment Options">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Fertility Treatment Options</h1>
			<p>A comprehensive overview of available fertility treatments, from first-line options to advanced reproductive technologies.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>Understanding Treatment Progression</h2>
		<p>Fertility treatment typically follows a step-wise approach, starting with less invasive and less expensive options before moving to more advanced treatments. Your doctor will recommend a path based on your diagnosis, age, and other factors.</p>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>Typical Treatment Progression:</strong> Lifestyle modifications → Ovulation induction medications → IUI → IVF → Third-party reproduction
		</div>

		<h2>First-Line Treatments</h2>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/medication/">Ovulation Induction Medications</a></h3>
			<p>Often the first step for women with irregular ovulation or unexplained infertility.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Clomiphene citrate (Clomid):</strong> Oral medication that stimulates ovulation</li>
				<li><strong>Letrozole (Femara):</strong> Aromatase inhibitor increasingly used as first-line treatment</li>
				<li><strong>Gonadotropins:</strong> Injectable hormones for more controlled stimulation</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> PCOS, irregular ovulation, mild unexplained infertility</p>
		</div>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/iui/">Intrauterine Insemination (IUI)</a></h3>
			<p>Prepared sperm is placed directly in the uterus during ovulation, reducing the distance sperm must travel.</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Can be done with natural cycle or combined with ovulation medications</li>
				<li>Less invasive than IVF with lower cost per cycle</li>
				<li>Success rates: 10-20% per cycle depending on diagnosis and age</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Mild male factor, unexplained infertility, cervical factor, use with donor sperm</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Advanced Reproductive Technology (ART)</h2>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/ivf/">In Vitro Fertilization (IVF)</a></h3>
			<p>The most effective fertility treatment, involving egg retrieval, fertilization in a laboratory, and embryo transfer.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Conventional IVF:</strong> Eggs and sperm combined in culture dish</li>
				<li><strong>ICSI:</strong> Single sperm injected directly into egg (used for male factor)</li>
				<li><strong>PGT:</strong> Preimplantation genetic testing of embryos</li>
				<li><strong>FET:</strong> Frozen embryo transfer (using previously frozen embryos)</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Blocked tubes, severe male factor, failed IUI, advanced maternal age, genetic concerns</p>
		</div>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/third-party/">Third-Party Reproduction</a></h3>
			<p>Options involving donors or gestational carriers.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Donor sperm:</strong> Used for male factor infertility or single/same-sex parents</li>
				<li><strong>Donor eggs:</strong> Used for diminished ovarian reserve or genetic concerns</li>
				<li><strong>Donor embryos:</strong> Embryos donated by other couples</li>
				<li><strong>Gestational surrogacy:</strong> Another woman carries the pregnancy</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Absent gametes, repeated IVF failure, uterine factor infertility</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Fertility Preservation</h2>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/preservation/">Egg, Sperm, and Embryo Freezing</a></h3>
			<p>Preserving fertility for future use.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Egg freezing:</strong> Recommended before age 38 for best outcomes</li>
				<li><strong>Sperm freezing:</strong> Simple process with high survival rates</li>
				<li><strong>Embryo freezing:</strong> Highest success rates for preservation</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Medical reasons (before cancer treatment), elective delay, gender transition</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Surgical Treatments</h2>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/surgical/">Surgical Interventions</a></h3>
			<p>Procedures to correct structural problems affecting fertility.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Laparoscopy:</strong> For endometriosis, ovarian cysts, tubal issues</li>
				<li><strong>Hysteroscopy:</strong> For uterine polyps, fibroids, scar tissue</li>
				<li><strong>Tubal surgery:</strong> Reversal of tubal ligation or repair</li>
				<li><strong>Varicocele repair:</strong> For male factor infertility</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Structural abnormalities, endometriosis, fibroids, tubal disease</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Recurrent Pregnancy Loss</h2>

		<div class="treatment-detail card">
			<h3><a href="/treatments/recurrent-loss/">Recurrent Pregnancy Loss (RPL)</a></h3>
			<p>Specialized evaluation and treatment after 2 or more consecutive miscarriages.</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Testing:</strong> Genetic, uterine, clotting disorders, hormonal evaluation</li>
				<li><strong>Treatments:</strong> Surgical correction, blood thinners, progesterone, IVF with PGT</li>
				<li><strong>Success rate:</strong> 60-75% even after 3 unexplained losses</li>
			</ul>
			<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Couples who have experienced multiple pregnancy losses</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Comparing Your Options</h2>
		<table>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Treatment</th>
					<th>Invasiveness</th>
					<th>Cost/Cycle</th>
					<th>Success Rate</th>
					<th>Time Investment</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>Medications alone</td>
					<td>Low</td>
					<td>$100-$1,500</td>
					<td>5-15%</td>
					<td>1 month</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>IUI</td>
					<td>Low-Medium</td>
					<td>$500-$4,000</td>
					<td>10-20%</td>
					<td>2-3 weeks</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>IVF</td>
					<td>High</td>
					<td>$12,000-$25,000</td>
					<td>40-65%*</td>
					<td>4-6 weeks</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Donor Egg IVF</td>
					<td>High</td>
					<td>$25,000-$45,000</td>
					<td>50-75%</td>
					<td>2-4 months</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>
		<p><em>*IVF success rates vary significantly by age and diagnosis. Rates shown are for women under 35 with favorable prognosis.</em></p>

		<div class="warning-box">
			<strong>Important:</strong> Success rates are averages and individual outcomes vary based on age, diagnosis, clinic experience, and other factors. Discuss your specific prognosis with your reproductive endocrinologist.
		</div>

		<p><a href="/decision-guide/">Use our Decision Guide</a> to explore which treatments might be right for your situation.</p>
	</section>
</Layout>

